HashMap collisions happen when two different keys produce the same hash index and are placed in the same bucket.
This is unavoidable because the number of possible keys is much larger than the number of buckets.

When does this happen?
When two keys have the same hashCode() result (or their hashes map to the same bucket index).
Example: "abc".hashCode() % 16 == "def".hashCode() % 16 (if the table size is 16).

Why do we need to solve it?
If collisions are not handled, one key could overwrite another, or you could lose data.
Without collision handling, you cannot reliably store and retrieve values.

What could be the issue?
Too many collisions (bad hash function or too small table) make lookups slow, as you have to search a long list/tree in a bucket.
If equals() is not implemented correctly, you may not find the right value even if it exists.

When is it okay to keep collisions?
Collisions are normal and expected; you just need to handle them efficiently.
If your hash function is good and your table is sized well, collisions will be rare and performance will be good.
You only need to worry if you see performance problems or if you use custom objects as keys and don’t override equals and hashCode properly.

Summary:
Collisions are normal in HashMap. You must handle them to avoid data loss and slow lookups. As long as you use a good hash function and implement equals/hashCode correctly, collisions are not a problem.